<p>A <b>fast Fourier transform</b> (<b>FFT</b>) is an <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> that compu=
tes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transform=
" title=3D"Discrete Fourier transform">discrete Fourier transform</a> (DFT)=
 of a sequence, or its inverse (IDFT). A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fourier transform">Fourier transform</a>=
 converts a signal from its original domain (often time or space) to a repr=
esentation in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency_domain=
" title=3D"Frequency domain">frequency domain</a> and vice versa.
</p><p>The DFT is obtained by decomposing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequence</a> of values into componen=
ts of different frequencies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_198=
4_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fo=
urier_transform#cite_note-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This o=
peration is useful in many fields, but computing it directly from the defin=
ition is often too slow to be practical. An FFT rapidly computes such trans=
formations by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_decomposition=
" title=3D"Matrix decomposition">factorizing</a> the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/DFT_matrix" title=3D"DFT matrix">DFT matrix</a> into a p=
roduct of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_matrix" title=3D"=
Sparse matrix">sparse</a> (mostly zero) factors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Loan_19=
92_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_F=
ourier_transform#cite_note-Loan_1992-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As a result, it manages =
to reduce the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_comple=
xity_theory" title=3D"Computational complexity theory">complexity</a> of co=
mputing the DFT from <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inlin=
e"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"dis=
play: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"=
{\textstyle O(n^{2})}">
