</p><p>As the FFT is merely an algebraic refactoring of terms within the DF=
T, the DFT and the FFT both perform mathematically equivalent and interchan=
geable operations, assuming that all terms are computed with infinite preci=
sion.  However, in the presence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Round-off_error" title=3D"Round-off error">round-off error</a>, many FFT a=
lgorithms are much more accurate than evaluating the DFT definition directl=
y or indirectly. There are many different FFT algorithms based on a wide ra=
nge of published theories, from simple <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex-number arithmetic</a>=
 to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"Group t=
heory">group theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number=
_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a>. The best-known FFT algo=
rithms depend upon the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorizati=
on" title=3D"Factorization">factorization</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, but there are FFTs with <span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mat=
hml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"ht=
tp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle O(n\log n)}">
