er-theoretic_transform" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Number-theoretic tra=
nsform">number-theoretic transforms</a>. Since the inverse DFT is the same =
as the DFT, but with the opposite sign in the exponent and a <span class=3D=
"texhtml">1/<i>n</i></span> factor, any FFT algorithm can easily be adapted=
 for it.
</p><p>Fast Fourier transforms are widely used for <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transform#Applications" title=3D"Discrete=
 Fourier transform">applications</a> in engineering, music, science, and ma=
thematics. The basic ideas were popularized in 1965, but some algorithms ha=
d been derived as early as 1805.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus=
_1984_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fas=
t_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
In 1994, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilbert_Strang" title=3D"=
Gilbert Strang">Gilbert Strang</a> described the FFT as "the most important=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_algorithm" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Numerical algorithm">numerical algorithm</a> of our life=
time",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Strang_1994_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Strang_1994-3=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and it =
was included in Top 10 Algorithms of 20th Century by the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"IEEE">IEEE</a> =
magazine <i>Computing in Science &amp; Engineering</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Dongarra_Sullivan_2000_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Dongarra_Sullivan_2000-5"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFast_Fourier_transform=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The development of fast algorithms for DFT was prefigured in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich=
 Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a>'s unpublished 1805 work on the orbits of a=
steroids <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2_Pallas" title=3D"2 Pall=
as">Pallas</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/3_Juno" title=
=3D"3 Juno">Juno</a>. Gauss wanted to interpolate the orbits from sample ob=
servations;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gauss_1866_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Gauss_18=
66-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1985_7-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transf=
orm#cite_note-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1985-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> his method was ver=
y similar to the one that would be published in 1965 by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cooley" title=3D"James Cooley">James Cooley</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Tukey" title=3D"John Tuk=
ey">John Tukey</a>, who are generally credited for the invention of the mod=
ern generic FFT algorithm. While Gauss's work predated even <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier" title=3D"Joseph Fourier">Joseph F=
ourier</a>'s 1822 results, he did not analyze the method's <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity" title=3D"Computational c=
omplexity">complexity</a>, and eventually used other methods to achieve the=
 same end.
</p><p>Between 1805 and 1965, some versions of FFT were published by other =
authors. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Yates" title=3D"Fra=
nk Yates">Frank Yates</a> in 1932 published his version called <i>interacti=
on algorithm</i>, which provided <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ast_Walsh%E2%80%93Hadamard_transform" title=3D"Fast Walsh=E2=80=93Hadamard =
transform">efficient computation of Hadamard and Walsh transforms</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Yates_1937_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Yates_1937-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Yates' algorithm is still used in the field of statistical design and analy=
sis of experiments. In 1942, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._C.=
_Danielson" title=3D"G. C. Danielson">G. C. Danielson</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornelius_Lanczos" title=3D"Cornelius Lanczos">=
Cornelius Lanczos</a> published their version to compute DFT for <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-ray_crystallography" title=3D"X-ray crysta=
llography">x-ray crystallography</a>, a field where calculation of Fourier =
transforms presented a formidable bottleneck.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Danielson_=
Lanczos_1942_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Danielson_Lanczos_1942-9"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lanczos_1956_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Lanczos_1956-10"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> While many methods in the past had focused on reducing the const=
ant factor for <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: =
