reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#=
cite_note-Gentleman_Sande_1966-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This method (and the general idea of an FFT) was popularized by a pu=
blication of Cooley and Tukey in 1965,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cooley_Tukey_1965=
_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fo=
urier_transform#cite_note-Cooley_Tukey_1965-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but it was late=
r discovered<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984_1-2" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#=
cite_note-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> that those two authors=
 had together independently re-invented an algorithm known to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich G=
auss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> around 1805<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gauss_1805_20=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fouri=
er_transform#cite_note-Gauss_1805-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (and subsequently redisco=
vered several times in limited forms).
</p><p>The best known use of the Cooley=E2=80=93Tukey algorithm is to divid=
e the transform into two pieces of size <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i>/2<=
/span> at each step, and is therefore limited to power-of-two sizes, but an=
y factorization can be used in general (as was known to both Gauss and Cool=
ey/Tukey<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984_1-3" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite=
_note-Heideman_Johnson_Burrus_1984-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>). These are called the <i>=
radix-2</i> and <i>mixed-radix</i> cases, respectively (and other variants =
such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Split-radix_FFT" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Split-radix FFT">split-radix FFT</a> have their o=
wn names as well).  Although the basic idea is recursive, most traditional =
implementations rearrange the algorithm to avoid explicit recursion. Also, =
because the Cooley=E2=80=93Tukey algorithm breaks the DFT into smaller DFTs=
, it can be combined arbitrarily with any other algorithm for the DFT, such=
 as those described below.
</p>
