https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Duhamel_Vett=
erli_1990-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Approximations">Approximati=
ons</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFast_Fou=
rier_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Ap=
proximations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>All of the FFT algorithms discussed above compute the DFT exactly (i.e.,=
 neglecting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Floating-point">floating-point</a> errors). A few=
 FFT algorithms have been proposed, however, that compute the DFT <i>approx=
imately</i>, with an error that can be made arbitrarily small at the expens=
e of increased computations. Such algorithms trade the approximation error =
for increased speed or other properties. For example, an approximate FFT al=
gorithm by Edelman et al. (1999)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Edelman_McCorquodale_To=
ledo_1999_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Edelman_McCorquodale_Toledo_1999-34"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> achieves lower communication requirements for <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_computing" title=3D"Parallel computing">paral=
lel computing</a> with the help of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fast_multipole_method" title=3D"Fast multipole method">fast multipole me=
thod</a>. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wavelet" title=3D"Wave=
let">wavelet</a>-based approximate FFT by Guo and Burrus (1996)<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Guo_Burrus_1996_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Guo_Burrus_1996-35"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> takes sparse inputs/outputs (time/frequency localization) into accoun=
t more efficiently than is possible with an exact FFT. Another algorithm fo=
r approximate computation of a subset of the DFT outputs is due to Shentov =
et al. (1995).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Shentov_Mitra_Heute_Hossen_1995_36-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_tran=
sform#cite_note-Shentov_Mitra_Heute_Hossen_1995-36"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Edelman=
 algorithm works equally well for sparse and non-sparse data, since it is b=
ased on the compressibility (rank deficiency) of the Fourier matrix itself =
rather than the compressibility (sparsity) of the data. Conversely, if the =
data are sparse=E2=80=94that is, if only <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> out of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> Fourier coefficients are nonzero=E2=80=94t=
hen the complexity can be reduced to <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle O(k\log n\log n/k)}">
  <semantics>
