e_note-libftsh-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A spherical-harmonic algorithm with <span cl=
ass=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-ma=
thml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"h=
ttp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>O</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mi>log</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}<=
/annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3515abfcc8eace588f5dc0a284d0a56e4b393d3c" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:11.172ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\textstyle O(n^{=
2}\log n)}"></span> complexity is described by Rokhlin and Tygert.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Rokhlin_Tygert_2006_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Rokhlin_Tygert_20=
06-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_folding_algorithm"=
 title=3D"Fast folding algorithm">fast folding algorithm</a> is analogous t=
o the FFT, except that it operates on a series of binned waveforms rather t=
han a series of real or complex scalar values. Rotation (which in the FFT i=
s multiplication by a complex phasor) is a circular shift of the component =
waveform.
</p><p>Various groups have also published FFT algorithms for non-equispaced=
 data, as reviewed in Potts <i>et al.</i> (2001).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Potts_=
Steidl_Tasche_2001_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Potts_Steidl_Tasche_2001-45"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Such algorithms do not strictly compute the DFT (which is only de=
fined for equispaced data), but rather some approximation thereof (a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-uniform_discrete_Fourier_transform" =
title=3D"Non-uniform discrete Fourier transform">non-uniform discrete Fouri=
er transform</a>, or NDFT, which itself is often computed only approximatel=
y). More generally, there are various other methods of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sp=
ectral estimation">spectral estimation</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFast_Fourier=
_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Appli=
cations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The FFT is used in digital recording, sampling, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Additive_synthesis" title=3D"Additive synthesis">additive =
synthesis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitch_correction=
" title=3D"Pitch correction">pitch correction</a> software.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_F=
ourier_transform#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The FFT's importance derives from the fact that it has made working =
in the frequency domain equally computationally feasible as working in the =
temporal or spatial domain. Some of the important applications of the FFT i=
nclude:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rockmore_2000_16-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Rockmore=
_2000-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Chu_George_1999_47-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cit=
e_note-Chu_George_1999-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>fast large-integer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multipl=
ication_algorithm" title=3D"Multiplication algorithm">multiplication algori=
thms</a> and polynomial multiplication,</li>
<li>efficient matrix=E2=80=93vector multiplication for <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toeplitz_matrix" title=3D"Toeplitz matrix">Toeplitz</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circulant" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Circulant">circulant</a> and other structured matrices,</li>
<li>filtering algorithms (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Over=
lap%E2%80%93add_method" title=3D"Overlap=E2=80=93add method">overlap=E2=80=
=93add</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overlap%E2%80%93sav=
e_method" title=3D"Overlap=E2=80=93save method">overlap=E2=80=93save</a> me=
thods),</li>
<li>fast algorithms for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_c=
osine_transform" title=3D"Discrete cosine transform">discrete cosine</a> or=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_sine_transform" title=3D=
"Discrete sine transform">sine transforms</a> (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_cosine_transform" title=3D"Discrete cosine trans=
form">fast DCT</a> used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JPEG" =
title=3D"JPEG">JPEG</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MPEG" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"MPEG">MPEG</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/MP3" title=3D"MP3">MP3</a> encoding and decoding),</li>
<li>fast <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chebyshev_approximation" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chebyshev approximation">Chebyshev approxima=
tion</a>,</li>
<li>solving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recurrence_relation" t=
itle=3D"Recurrence relation">difference equations</a>,</li>
<li>computation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_spectromet=
ry" title=3D"Mass spectrometry">isotopic distributions</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Fernandez-de-Cossio_2012_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Fernandez-de-Cossio_2=
012-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>modulation and demodulation of complex data symbols using <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_frequency-division_multiplexing" tit=
le=3D"Orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing">orthogonal frequency-divi=
sion multiplexing</a> (OFDM) for 5G, LTE, Wi-Fi, DSL, and other modern comm=
unication systems.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Alternatives">Alternatives<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFast_Fourier=
_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Alter=
natives"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete-time_Fouri=
er_transform" title=3D"Discrete-time Fourier transform">Discrete-time Fouri=
er transform</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_wavelet=
_transform" title=3D"Discrete wavelet transform">Discrete wavelet transform=
</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Hilbert_transfo=
rm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete Hilbert transform">Discrete Hil=
bert transform</a></div>
<p>The FFT can be a poor choice for analyzing signals with <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-stationary" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non=
-stationary">non-stationary</a> frequency content=E2=80=94where the frequen=
cy characteristics change over time. DFTs provide a global frequency estima=
te, assuming that all frequency components are present throughout the entir=
e signal, which makes it challenging to detect short-lived or transient fea=
tures within signals.
</p><p>For cases where frequency information appears briefly in the signal =
or generally varies over time, alternatives like the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Short-time_Fourier_transform" title=3D"Short-time Fourie=
r transform">short-time Fourier transform</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Discrete_wavelet_transform" title=3D"Discrete wavelet transfor=
m">discrete wavelet transforms</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Discrete_Hilbert_transform" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete Hi=
lbert transform">discrete Hilbert transform</a> can be more suitable.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_=
transform#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These transforms allow for localized f=
requency analysis by capturing both frequency and time-based information.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Research_areas">Research ar=
eas</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFast_Fou=
rier_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: R=
esearch areas"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<dl><dt>Big FFTs</dt>
<dd>With the explosion of big data in fields such as astronomy, the need fo=
r 512K FFTs has arisen for certain interferometry calculations. The data co=
llected by projects such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WMAP" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"WMAP">WMAP</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/LIGO" title=3D"LIGO">LIGO</a> require FFTs of tens of billi=
ons of points. As this size does not fit into main memory, so-called out-of=
-core FFTs are an active area of research.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cormen_Nicol_=
1998_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fas=
t_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Cormen_Nicol_1998-51"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dt>Approximate FFTs</dt>
<dd>For applications such as MRI, it is necessary to compute DFTs for nonun=
iformly spaced grid points and/or frequencies. Multipole-based approaches c=
an compute approximate quantities with factor of runtime increase.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Dutt_Rokhlin_1993_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Dutt_Rokhlin_1993-5=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></dd>
<dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform_on_finite_gr=
oups" title=3D"Fourier transform on finite groups">Group FFTs</a></dt>
<dd>The FFT may also be explained and interpreted using <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_representation_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Group representation theory">group representation theory</a>, allowi=
ng for further generalization. A function on any compact group, including n=
on-cyclic, has an expansion in terms of a basis of irreducible matrix eleme=
nts. It remains an active area of research to find an efficient algorithm f=
or performing this change of basis. Applications including efficient <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_harmonic" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Spherical harmonic">spherical harmonic</a> expansion, analyzing =
certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_process" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Markov process">Markov processes</a>, robotics etc.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Rockmore_2004_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-Rockmore_2004-53"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></dd>
<dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_Fourier_transform" tit=
le=3D"Quantum Fourier transform">Quantum FFTs</a></dt>
<dd>Shor's fast algorithm for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inte=
ger_factorization" title=3D"Integer factorization">integer factorization</a=
> on a quantum computer has a subroutine to compute DFT of a binary vector.=
 This is implemented as a sequence of 1- or 2-bit quantum gates now known a=
s quantum FFT, which is effectively the Cooley=E2=80=93Tukey FFT realized a=
s a particular factorization of the Fourier matrix. Extensions to these ide=
as are currently being explored.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform#cite_note-=
54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup></dd></dl>
